body:
I tried this code:

```rust
trait MyTrait {
    type Value;
}
struct S<T: MyTrait>(T::Value);
// Form 1
impl<T: MyTrait<Value = i32>> From<T::Value> for S<T> {
    fn from(x: T::Value) -> Self {
        Self(x)
    }
}
// Form 2
impl<T: MyTrait<Value = i32>> From<i32> for S<T>
{
    fn from(x: i32) -> Self {
        Self(x)
    }
}
```

I expected to see this happen: 
**Both** form 1 or form 2 compiles. Because form 1 and form 2 are basically the same.

Instead, this happened: 
**Only** form 2 compiles. The compiler fails to infer that `T::Value` is the same as `i32` where `T: MyTrait<Value = i32>>`.
```log
error[E0119]: conflicting implementations of trait `std::convert::From<S<_>>` for type `S<_>`
 --> src/main.rs:5:1
  |
5 | impl<T: MyTrait<Value = i32>> From<T::Value> for S<T> {
  | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
  |
  = note: conflicting implementation in crate `core`:
          - impl<T> From<T> for T;

```
